message.content:
1. Transitive verb - A transitive verb is a verb that takes an object or direct object, such as "I gave her the book" or "He killed the man."
2. Intransitive verb - An intransitive verb is a verb that does not take an object or direct object, such as "She smiled" or "The sun rose."
3. Auxiliary verb - An auxiliary verb is a helping verb that modifies another verb but does not take the main action of the sentence, such as "was" or "will".
4. Copula verb - A copula verb expresses a relationship between two subjects, such as "he and I are friends."
5. Modal verb - A modal verb is used to express possibility, necessity, permission, ability, or ability, among other things, such as "must" or "could".
6. Linking verb - A linking verb connects the subject of a sentence with an object or complements it, such as "to be", "to have", or "to become."
